THE RISK:
{
 "id": "psu-shelf-cagr-divergence-erodes-tambase",
 "title": "The model's own cross-check source is measuring the substitution: PDU+PSU spend growing 21% while rack-PDU grows 9% means the PDU share of rack power is falling every year",
 "narrative": "tamBase's high-end cross-check takes BIS/R&M's Europe PDUs+PSUs figure ($2.45B, 2024) and applies a static ~55% PDU share to get the €495M ceiling. But look at the growth rates the ledger itself carries: the combined PDUs+PSUs category is forecast at 21.23% CAGR while rack-PDU-only sources cluster at 9–9.7%. Arithmetic forces the gap into the non-PDU component — PSUs and power shelves, the very substitutes the boundary excludes — which must be growing at roughly 30%+ to reconcile the two series. That divergence is not a data quirk; it is the substitution trend expressed in euros. A static 55% PDU share is wrong in the direction that matters: it decays each year of the venture's window, dragging both the cross-check ceiling and the curated €320M toward the band's low end even if data-center construction booms.",
 "category": "model-structure",
 "targetNodes": [
  "tamBase"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "BIS/R&M forecast the Europe PDUs+PSUs market at 21.23% CAGR ($2.45B→$20.05B by 2035), while rack-PDU-only forecasts cluster at 9.7% (GVR) — a 2.2x growth-rate gap within overlapping scopes",
   "refs": [
    "digest:tam-base#c2",
    "digest:tam-base#c3",
    "digest:tam-base#c0"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The growth gap is mathematically absorbed by the PSU/power-shelf component of the combined category — the excluded substitutes — meaning the PDU value share of European rack power declines every year; the ledger's cross-check applies a static ~55% PDU share to derive the €495M ceiling",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:tamBase",
    "digest:tam-base#c4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "Both the €495M high edge and the curated €320M assume PDU share of rack-power spend holds through the sizing window; if the share is decaying at the rate the two CAGRs imply, the effective 2026-27 PDU-only base sits below the curated value and the 240–520 band is skewed high, not symmetric",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:tamBase",
    "digest:tam-base#c5"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The cross-check looks like belt-and-braces diligence — two independent chains landing in one band. Nobody re-reads the two sources' CAGRs against each other, because CAGR is filed under 'growth outlook' (shape.cagr, not funnel-active) rather than 'base-year scope decay'. The tension hides in a ratio between two numbers that are both individually in the model.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "The IndexBox EU Rack PDUs report (or Omdia's 2024-base rack-PDU tracker) showing the PDU share of European rack-power/PSU spend stable or rising 2024–2027.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.55,
  "rationale": "The CAGR divergence is in the model's own attached evidence and is arithmetically unavoidable; the uncertainty is whether BIS's 21.23% is inflated (aggressive forecast) rather than a true substitution signal — publisher spread on adjacent categories (>2x) means moderate confidence, not high. [evidence revision: The falsifier search returned no evidence of stable/rising PDU share; instead the intended falsifying sources (IndexBox rack PDU) confirmed a much lower rack-PDU growth rate (5–8%, or 10–12% for intelligent PDUs) versus the 21.23% combined series, and QY Research independently confirms the power-shelf/PSU substitute category growing ~26.5%. This triangulation raises confidence that the growth gap reflects a real substitution/share-decay signal rather than merely an inflated BIS forecast. Held below 0.7 because the two series are not scope-identical (global AI-cluster PSU vs Europe combined) and the exact PDU share and its decay rate within the sizing window (2026–27) remain uncomputed from the abstracts.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "tamBase",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 265,
   "note": "PDU share of the combined rack-power category decays ~3-4pp/yr from the assumed 55%, pulling the effective PDU-only base below the curated midpoint"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Revenue mix between rack-PDU and PSU/power-shelf product lines at incumbents",
   "where": "Vertiv quarterly earnings (critical power segment detail); Delta Electronics and LiteOn investor materials (OCP power-shelf suppliers)",
   "threshold": "Shelf/PSU lines growing >2x the PDU line for two consecutive quarters",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Updated rack-PDU-only vs PDU+PSU base-year figures at next report vintages",
   "where": "Grand View Research rack-PDU update (2026 vintage); Research and Markets/BIS Europe PDUs+PSUs update",
   "threshold": "Implied PDU share of the combined category dropping below 50%",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Purchase the IndexBox EU Rack PDUs report ($4,000) to pin the PDU-only European base directly and remove dependence on the static 55% share assumption",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "tamBase",
   "note": "Named in the ledger's own promotion path; also resolves the Europe≈30% unsourced regional split"
  },
  {
   "action": "Re-run the sizing annually with a time-varying PDU-share parameter instead of a static split, so substitution decay is visible in the funnel rather than hidden in the band",
   "type": "operational",
